<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Communique Accuses UN of `Provocations' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serb Communique Accuses UN of `Provocations' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604171794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1652 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Banja Luka, April 26 (TANJUG) -- The Bosnian Serb 
Army (VRS) on Tuesday [26 April] warned it would `do everything 
to protect the lives' of its members and civilians if members of 
the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) continued to open fire on 
Serb positions and settlements in northern Bosnia, as it said 
they had often done in the past ten days. A communique released 
by the VRS First Krajina Corps said that UNPROFOR provocations 
had been frequent on the Doboj front in the past 30 days, and 
that the UNPROFOR command had failed to take any steps to 
prevent them, that is, to prevent the direct siding of the 
international forces with the Muslims, although its attention 
had been drawn to the fact more than once. The communique said 
it was regrettable that the silence on the part of higher 
UNPROFOR commands meant their tacit approval of further 
provocations by UNPROFOR units. 
  The failure of UNPROFOR commands to respond to the addressed 
warnings seems to have encouraged UNPROFOR units to continue 
staging military provocations, which have not been countered by 
the Serb side, the communique said. The communique said one had 
the impression that the direct goal of such UNPROFOR actions was 
to provoke a response from Serb forces and then accuse them of 
attacking U.N. peace-keepers, which could be used as a pretext 
for air strikes against Serb positions, the communique set out. 
The communique specified that an UNPROFOR helicopter flew over 
Serb positions in the area of Banovici several times on Monday 
and opened fire on them. The communique said U.N. peace-keepers 
in the occupied Serb village of Poljice, near Maglaj, had 
several times opened fire on Serb settlements and positions on 
the western slopes of Mount Ozren, and that UNPROFOR units in 
Zavidovici had opened fire from armoured vehicles on the Serb 
settlement of Dolac. 
  Columns of armoured UNPROFOR vehicles coming from Lukavac 
practically daily demonstrate force only a hundred meters or so 
from VRS positions at Milino Selo, Sizje and Donja Brijesnica, 
the communique said. The communique recalled Bosnian Croat 
reports according to which U.N. peace-keepers are installing 
radar systems for the detection of Serb artillery positions in 
the area of Maglaj and regularly sending on the relevant 
information to Muslim units. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

