<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG: Muslim-Croat Relations `Still Tense' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    TANJUG: Muslim-Croat Relations `Still Tense' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604011394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2312 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604011394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 25 (TANJUG) -- A bomb blast 
destroyed a mosque in Croat-controlled Livno in southwestern 
Bosnia early on Monday morning, Croatian radio confirmed. In 
addition to Zepce, Kiseljak, and West Mostar, Livno is now the 
fourth town in the Croat republic of Herzeg-Bosnia, the state of 
Bosnian Croats, in which Croats have destroyed all Moslem 
religious objects. Bosnian Croats and Moslems, who fought 
bitter battles for territories since the spring of last year, 
especially in central and southern Bosnia-Herzegovina, signed an 
agreement on a bi-national federation early this year under 
strong pressure of Washington. As agreed, the federation would 
later enter into a confederation with neighbouring croatia. 
  Despite the signed agreement, Croat-Moslem relations are 
still tense. This is evident also in the limited freedom of 
movement for Moslem civilians and Moslem-owened vehicles in 
certain parts of Croat-controlled Bosnia-Herzegovina. The two 
sides also disagree on the issue of who will be the first 
president of their common state, although the deadline for this 
has long passed. The Croatian side demands that the first 
president be a Croat, but is willing to agree to a compromise 
solution -- that the president be a Moslem (Haris Silajdzic) but 
not Bosnian Moslem leader Alija Izetbegovic who has been 
nominated for this office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

