<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic: `Keys to War' in Hands of Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Izetbegovic: `Keys to War' in Hands of Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604185994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2604185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, president of the Presidency of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, has sent letters to U.S. President Clinton, 
Russian President Yeltsin, and Saudi King Fahd, in which he asks 
them to follow the situation in Gorazde after NATO's ultimatum, 
and to launch new initiatives for the political settlement of 
the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina. In his letter to Russian 
President Yeltsin, President Izetbegovic says, among other 
things, the following: 
  We have received with pleasure and hope your firm 
condemnation of the bloodshed among the civilians in Gorazde. 
We favor a political solution to the conflict. However, the 
aggressor is not giving up the idea of destroying Bosnia and 
exterminating our people even after two years. The keys to the 
war in Bosnia-Herzegovina are in the hands of Belgrade and Pale, 
the letter states. In our hands are only the keys of resistance 
and determination to persevere in this unfair struggle between 
good and evil, between democracy and fascism. Esteemed Mr. 
President, we welcome the activities of your government with 
regard to Bosnia-Herzegovina. At the end of the letter to Boris 
Yeltsin, President Alija Izetbegovic officially invites the 
Russian President to visit Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  In his letter to Saudi King Fahd, President Alija 
Izetbegovic 
stressed his demand that in future peace talks on our country, 
in addition to the United States, Russia, the United Nations, 
and the European Union, the Conference of Islamic Countries also 
take part as a fifth equal member. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

