<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian Withdrawal From Gorazde Confirmed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian Withdrawal From Gorazde Confirmed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604223794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2229 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 26 (TANJUG) -- Representatives of 
the United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) said on Tuesday 
evening that Bosnian Serb forces have withdrawn their heavy 
weapons to outside a 20km zone from the inner core of Gorazde, 
as provided for under the NATO ultimatum, and that there is no 
longer a threat of air strikes against their positions. Gorazde 
is a Moslem enclave in the east of civil war-torn 
Bosnia-Herzegovina where Serb and Moslem forces clashed heavily 
for almost a month. The NATO Council threatened it would bomb 
Bosnian Serb positions unless they withdrew their heavy weapons 
to a distance of 20km from the center of Gorazde by 00:01 GMT 
Wednesday. 
  The UNPROFOR representatives in Sarajevo declined to specify 
if all Serb heavy weapons had been withdrawn from the area, but 
said that there was no longer a threat of air strikes. 
Confirming this, U.N. Spokesman Eric Chaperon said that the 
U.N. force commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina, General Michael 
Rose was going to bed. Chaperon also said that Moslems had 
fired at an UNPROFOR patrol which was checking the Serb 
positions in the vicinity of Gorazde. There were no casualties, 
he said, but a protest has been sent to the Moslem authorities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9577 </DOCNO>
