<H3> <TI>   Serbs Reportedly `Entrenching' in Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Reportedly `Entrenching' in Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804150794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2804150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Fahrudin Becic from Gorazde] </F>
  [Text] Not only have they not withdrawn to the distance of 
3 km, but the chetniks are also entrenching as close as 1 km to 
the city center. At about 1300, a small group of them came down 
to UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] personnel carriers situated 
some 350 meters from the hospital. With UNPROFOR approval, the 
chetniks are continuing settling their civilians inside the 3 km 
zone. This is what is happening in Zubcici, south of the town. 
This is what is happening east of the town, in the suburbs of 
(?Fazagici) and (?Pubjeri). 
  One should also say that all these three villages are 
villages that were populated exclusively by Muslims before the 
war. A (?similar) situation is in Kopaci, which is more than 3 
km from the city center. The chetniks are also settling people 
there. Looting on the entire occupied territory is drawing to 
an end. According to the information of the Army of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina in Gorazde, artillery weapons have not been 
removed from the majority of the strongholds between Cajnice and 
Foca. Of course, in some cases, they were only redeployed to 
new positions, close to [words indistinct] This refers to 
(?Nekopi), Zebina Suma, [word indistinct], Djakovici, and many 
other locations. 
  This is Fahrudin Becic reporting for the Radio and 
Television 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

