<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Continuing Strike </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Continuing Strike </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Striking Miners Put Forward Demands </H4>

<F P=102> LD2804215294 Warsaw PAP in Polish 2041 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2804215294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 28 Apr--During Thursday's talks between 
Industry and Trade Minister Marek Pol and the striking lignite 
miners, the unionists submitted their six demands. Three of 
these are of a nationwide nature; the other three apply to their 
branch of industry. The sides discussed demands put forward by 
industry branches as well as a timetable for further talks. 
  Late in the evening, following a meeting with Solidarity 
leader Marian Krzaklewski, the miners demanded that a fixed date 
be given for the coming into force of the Enterprise Pact. 
  Following Minister Pol's 26 April decision to cancel the 
restructuring of the lignite mining industry, the miners 
promised that they will deliver enough coal to power stations 
before 2000 on Thursday so that they will be able to generate 
power to about one-third of their total capacity. If the 
government fails to present a timetable for the implementation 
of Solidarity demands after that time, the unionists have warned 
that protest action will escalate. 
  Miners striking in the Belchatow and Turow mines have been 
delivering coal in the quantities agreed upon Tuesday, while 
awaiting the outcome of talks held in Konin, PAP correspondents 
were told on at 2200 on Thursday. 

</TEXT>

