<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Minister Backs Tough Anti-Inflation Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Minister Backs Tough Anti-Inflation Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804201794 Warsaw TV Polonia Network in Polish 1730 GMT 28 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2804201794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TV Polonia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tomorrow morning President Lech Walesa will hand 
Grzegorz Kolodko his act of appointment to the post of deputy 
prime minister and finance minister. Professor Kolodko was 
already a candidate for finance minister during the creation of 
Waldemar Pawlak's Cabinet last fall. He relinquished 
participation in the government at that time because the 
economic program he presented was not accepted by the whole 
coalition. 
  [Unidentified Correspondent] Prof. Kolodko, who already took 
part today in a meeting of the Council of Ministers' Economic 
and Social Committees, said that he identified with the 
government's position on the strikes and the neopopiwek 
[wage-control law]. 
  [Begin Kolodko recording] I never was an advocate of the 
neopopiwek, but I always was and remain an advocate of a tough 
anti-inflation policy. The government will shortly be proposing 
solutions that will, after acceptance by the trade unions, serve 
to protect real wages, which the prime minister spoke about, and 
here the issue of the popiwek, the neopopiwek, should be seen in 
the proper perspective. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

