<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Meets With U.S. Ambassador in Zagreb </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman Meets With U.S. Ambassador in Zagreb </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804145994 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2804145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatian President Dr. Franjo Tudjman received Peter 
Galbraith, U.S. ambassador to Croatia, in the Presidential 
Palace today. President Tudjman told Ambassador Galbraith that 
the examination of proposals and negotiations on signing an 
agreement between the Croatian Government and the U.S. 
Government on economic and technical aid, to be granted to 
Croatia via the U.S. Agency for International Development, which 
is a constituent part of the State Department, should 
immediately be embarked upon. The agreement is expected to be 
signed at the beginning of May. 
  Ambassador Galbraith informed President Tudjman of his 
country's intention to begin negotiations on certain concrete 
projects immediately after the agreement has been signed. He 
also told him that an agreement on agricultural cooperation to 
the value of $10 million will be signed at the Croatian Ministry 
of Finance. President Tudjman expressed his pleasure at the 
progress achieved in talks between the National Bank of Croatia 
and the Croatian Finance Ministry on the one hand, and the World 
Bank and the IMF on the other, that have been held in Washington 
over the past few days. 
  President Tudjman and Ambassador Galbraith also discussed 
the 
situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina and the UN protected areas [in 
Croatia], a statement from the president's office says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

