<H3> <TI>   Language Issue Delays Bulgarian Treaties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Language Issue Delays Bulgarian Treaties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604212394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2015 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2604212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 26 Apr (TANJUG) -- Macedonian [Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] President Kiro Gligorov 
has returned from Sofia this evening following his first 
official visit to Bulgaria, and positively assessed his two-day 
"very open" talks with Bulgarian officials. 
  Gligorov said that two treaties on Skopje-Sofia cooperation 
that were to have been signed -- on the elimination of double 
taxation and the protection of mutual investments -- have not 
been signed because of the refusal by Bulgarian officials to 
sign these documents also in the Macedonian language. According 
to Gligorov, the Macedonian delegation deemed that the 
Macedonian language could not be a contentious issue and that 
the right of every nation is to call the language it speaks as 
it pleases. 
  However, President Gligorov expressed the hope that talks of 
this kind would gradually yield results. Gligorov also 
expressed the conviction that Bulgarian President Zhelev "has an 
understanding of this issue," but that "they should clarify this 
matter in Bulgaria on their own." 
  The Macedonian president also said that journalists at a 
news 
conference in Sofia were most interested in the possiblity of 
Macedonia joining a former Yugoslav republic or some neighboring 
state. According to him, this is an issue that has been decided 
once and for all, because Macedonia has become a free, 
sovereign, and independent country and no other option can be 
taken into consideration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

