<H3> <TI>   President Holds Security Cabinet Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Holds Security Cabinet Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3103023494 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3103023494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Elizabeth Diaz Sotero at Los Pinos Presidencial </F>
Palace from the "ACIR Radio News" newscast] 
  [Text] At noon today, we said that calm had returned to the 
official Los Pinos residence. But this does not mean inactivity. 
At approximately 1400 today, the president held a meeting with 
members of the national security cabinet: National Defense 
Secretary Antonio Riviello Bazan, Government Secretary Jorge 
Carpizo McGregor, Attorney General Diego Valadez, Federal 
District Attorney General Humberto Benitez Trevillo, and 
National Security General Director Jorge Tello Pon. 
  Although we do not have any official information on this 
meeting, we believe the president and his officials must have 
discussed, among other matters, the appointment of Dr. Cordoba 
Montoya as Mexico's new permanent representative to the 
Inter-American Development Bank, headquartered in Washington; 
the general situation in the country; Chiapas issues; Luis 
Donaldo Colosio's murder; and, quite probably, how Mexico and 
especially Mexico City will get along in the coming days. 
  Although it has not been officially announced, it seems 
President Salinas de Gortari will take a few days of rest after 
all and go to Agualeguas, Nuevo Leon. This is one of two times 
during the year that he takes a holiday. This has not been 
officially confirmed, but it seems everything is ready for him 
in Agualeguas. Therefore, he must have talked with his officials 
about how things will go in Mexico City during his probable 
absence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9655 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat062_c_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-062 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidency Office Chief Named Representative to IDB </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidency Office Chief Named Representative to IDB </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3103015294 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3103015294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Alma Rosa Baez at the Mexican Finance Secretariat </F>
from the "ACIR Radio News" newscast] 
  [Text] Good afternoon. The Finance Secretariat has issued a 
short communique that reads as follows: 
  Dr. Pedro Aspe, the finance and public credit secretary, has 
appointed Dr. Jose Cordoba Montoya as the Mexican representative 
to the Inter-American Development Bank [IDB], which has its 
headquarters in Washington. Dr. Jose Cordoba was chief of the 
Office of the Presidency of the republic until today. 
  The Finance Secretariat has not released any more details on 
this information. It is important, however, to tell our 
listeners that the IDB governors will meet in Guadalajara from 8 
to 13 April. Mexico is hosting this meeting. It will be the 
first official event handled by Mr. Jose Cordoba Montoya. 
Cordoba Montoya was the chief of the Office of the Presidency of 
the republic and, until today, was in charge of all the advisers 
of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari. 
  The IDB is very important within the international economic 
sector. It groups all nations, especially developing nations. At 
least 23 countries are expected to attend the meeting in 
Guadalajara. Representatives of all those countries will meet 
with the IDB in that city. Jose Cordoba Montoya will probably 
have to move to Washington because all the governors handle 
their countries' IDB concerns from its headquarters. This is the 
information we have now. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

