<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Colombian Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Colombian Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3003132794 </F>
<F P=103> PA3003132794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments monitored through 29 
March. 
  The National Administrative Department of Statistics, DANE, 
has disclosed that in 1993 commercial trade increased 4.25 
percent, due primarily to an increase in the sale of furniture 
and electrical appliances which, in turn, was prompted by 
increased construction. DANE figures show that sales in December 
increased by 8.79 percent compared to the same period on 1992. 
Vehicles and replacement parts sold the most at 15.62 percent, 
and fuel and lubricants sold the least at minus 7.26 percent. 
Although sales were up, jobs decreased by 1.48 percent in 
comparison to 1992. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 17 
Mar 94 p 4B) 
  The prices of staple products continue to increase in a 
worrisome manner. During the first 10 days of March the cost of 
living increased by 1.94 percent, which usually happens every 
month, but the government fears that if the trend continues 
throughout the month the quarterly cost of living rate could 
increase to up to 10 percent. Some analysts believe the excess 
of money in circulation is also a factor. In 1993 food, which 
represents 34 percent of the cost of living, increased by only 
14.5 percent. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 18 Mar 
pp 1, 1B) 
  Foreign investment in Colombia increased by 8.6 percent in 
January compared to the same month in 1993. Total investment, 
excluding petroleum, was $21.7 million in January 1994 compared 
to $19.9 million in January 1993. The Investing in Colombia 
Corporation reported that 89.7 percent of this investment went 
to the mining sector. The manufacturing sector received 6.2 
percent. The United Kingdom was the top investor with $17.4 
million, that is, 84.4 percent of total foreign investment in 
Colombia in January 1994. All of it went to the mining sector. 
The United States was second with 13.1 percent and it also 
invested in the mining sector. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in 
Spanish 19 Mar 94 p 3B) 
  Colombian purchases abroad increased by 47.2 percent between 
January and November 1993 compared to the same period in 1992. 
Exports grew by only 2.7 percent in the same period. According 
to DANE, imports totaled $8.948 billion, and exports totaled 
$6.504 billion. Economists think that this is due to the 
revaluation of the peso. The import of consumer and capital 
goods and construction materials experienced the highest growth 
rate, more than 70 percent. The import of vehicles grew by 148 
percent and the import of weapons by 215 percent. Exports 
increased from $6.332 billion to $6.504. Traditional exports, 
such as coffee, petroleum, coal, and ferrous nickel 
[ferroniquel], dropped by 6.46 percent. Meanwhile, 
nontraditional exports grew by 11.37 percent. (Santa Fe de 
Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 19 Mar 94 p 3B) 
  The Board of the Cartagena Accord has reported that the 
exchange of goods and services among the members of the Andean 
Group, comprised by Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and 
Venezuela, reached $2.886 billion in 1993, that is, a 
117-percent increase compared to 1990. Excluding fuel, exports 
among Andean countries in 1993 reached $2.642 billion, a 34.1 
percent increase compared to 1992. In 1993 Colombia exported 
$1,159,800,000 or 40.2 percent of total intra-subregional trade. 
Venezuela was the main destination for Colombian exports. 
Sales to that country totaled $711.6 million. Venezuela was 
the second Andean Group exporter with $987.5 million or 34.2 
percent of total intra-subregional sales. Most Venezuelan 
exports went to Colombia. Ecuador registered the largest 
increase in intra-subregional exports with 76 percent. Bolivia 
increased exports by 8 percent and Peru by 10.4 percent in 1993. 
(Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 23 Mar 94 pp 1B, 3B) 
  Foreign Trade Minister Juan Manuel Santos and Agriculture 
Minister Jose Antonio Ocampo sent a letter dated 23 March to the 
newspaper EL TIEMPO stating that the government is not planning 
to reduce tariffs on and protective measures for the 
agricultural sector, or alter the price of agricultural produce 
in order to stop the rise of inflation. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL 
TIEMPO in Spanish 24 Mar 94 p 8A) 
  The members of the Association of Coffee Producers on 24 
March decided to reduce from 20 percent to 10 percent their 
withholding of exportable coffee, a measure they have 
implemented since October 1993. They had agreed that as soon as 
the price of coffee reached 75 cents per pound they would cut 
withholding by half. This in fact happened because the price of 
coffee was over 75 cents yesterday. This decision was made 
during a meeting in London. The member countries decided to 
continue this strategy because it has so far produced good 
results. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 25 Mar 94 p 1B) 
  The next government must manage the petroleum bonanza very 
prudently and save part of those resources if it wants to come 
out a winner from one of the greatest economic challenges of 
recent years. President Cesar Gaviria, World Bank officials, and 
international experts made this recommendation yesterday at the 
opening of a seminar organized by the National Planning 
Department. President Gaviria said that the Cusiana oil fields 
must be used to decrease poverty levels and achieve a sustained 
growth rate. The country currently has a reserve of 3.6 billion 
barrels of petroleum. Gaviria pointed out that the country must 
continue its search for new oil fields. Gaviria urged his 
successor to follow the example of Indonesia, which progressed 
after a petroleum boom. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 
25 Mar 94 p 1B) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

