<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central American Leaders on New PRI Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central American Leaders on New PRI Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3003125394 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0205 GMT 30 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3003125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 20 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Central American 
leaders today praised the designation of Ernesto Zedillo by the 
ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) as candidate for 
the Mexican presidency, replacing Luis Donaldo Colosio. 
Zedillo, a former secretary of planning and budget and of 
public education, was campaign manager for candidate Colosio, 
who was killed last week by two shots in the city of Tijuana, in 
northwestern Mexico. 
  In a statement for NOTIMEX via telephone after learning of 
Zedillo's designation, Guatemalan President Ramiro De Leon 
Carpio called for "strengthening relations with Mexico based on 
respect for sovereignty and self-determination." Meanwhile, 
Obdulio Chinchilla, president of the Finance Commission of the 
Guatemalan Congress, said should Zedillo win the Mexican 
elections on 21 August "there will be an opportunity to 
restructure more dynamic commercial relations with Mexico." 
  In Managua, Nicaraguan President Violeta de Chamorro, 
through 
government spokesman Luis Rivas Leyva, expressed hope that the 
PRI decision will continue maintain the normal course of the 
Mexican electoral process. 
  Panamanian President Guillermo Endara commented in Panama 
City that Zedillo's appointment was "a good selection." 
  Costa Rican Vice President German Serrano Pinto said "Mexico 
has shown it has overcome the recent unfortunate events and 
continues on the democratic path." 
  Nils Castro, one of the vice presidents of the Permanent 
Conference of Latin American Political Parties (COPPPAL) 
expressed his hope that the new presidential candidate "will 
continue the same campaign program and the same government 
platform" as Colosio. 
  In San Salvador, Ren Figueroa, deputy of the ruling 
Nationalist Republican Alliance, said that "we do not doubt 
Zedillo will follow the same path as Colosio, as he was one of 
his closest collaborators." 
  Ciro Cruz Zepeda, secretary general of the Salvadoran 
National Conciliation Party (PCN), said the new PRI presidential 
candidate "is the best man" to assume that responsibility. 

</TEXT>

