<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazilian Foreign Minister Confirms Wheat Purchase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Brazilian Foreign Minister Confirms Wheat Purchase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY3003153394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2350 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY3003153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 24 Mar (EFE) -- Brazilian Foreign 
Minister Celso Amorim has assured his Argentine counterpart 
Guido Di Tella that Brazil will exceed its commitment to 
purchase a minimum of 2 million tonnes of wheat from Argentina 
during 1994. 
  In a note sent yesterday and disseminated today, 24 March, 
Amorim reiterated his government's willingness to maintain 
regular contacts with Argentine officials to follow up 
developments on wheat imports. 
  Amorim added that the Brazilian Foreign Trade Secretariat is 
investigating Brazilian wheat purchases from Canada and Germany 
in terms of GATT provisions concerning "dumping" and subsidies. 
  Amorim described the imports of Argentine wheat as 
"strategic" for the implementation of the Program for 
Integration and Cooperation developed by the two countries since 
1986. 
  Amorim said that Brazilian mills "were the first to 
acknowledge that the purchase of Argentine wheat is more 
advantageous in light of tariff reductions provided under the 
Common Market of the South (Mercosur), the exemption of other 
duties, and lower freight costs stemming from the fact that 
Argentina and Brazil are neighbors." 
  Amorim noted that the estimated amount of wheat Brazil will 
have to import this harvest year to meet domestic needs stands 
at 5.6 million tonnes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

