<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY3103220394 </F>
<F P=103> PY3103220394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Brazil monitored through 31 
March. 
  The Sao Paulo Commercial Federation reported that February 
sales in Sao Paulo increased 12.28 percent compared with the 
same month in 1993, and that this has been the best level of 
sales in the country in the last three years. (Brasilia Voz do 
Brasil Network in Portuguese 2200 GMT 25 Mar 94) 
  A merger between Brastemp and Consul, both of which belong 
to 
the Brasmotor Group, was announced on 24 March by the holding 
company's president, Hugo Miguel Etchenique. The new company, 
whose merger must still be approved at an April stockholders' 
meeting, will be called Multibras, Inc. Household Appliances. 
The new company's sales will initially total $800 million per 
year with exports of $100 million. Multibras will have 10,000 
employees. Etchenique said he will not shut down any factories 
or cut manufacturing. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in 
Portuguese 25 Mar 94 Economy Section p B12) 
  Fuel prices will be increased 19.25 percent as of 26 March, 
the Finance Ministry announced on 25 March. Average fuel price 
increases totaled 42.5 percent in March as of 24 March. (Sao 
Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 25 Mar 94 p 16) 
  Finance Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso and Sao Paulo 
Governor Luiz Antonio Fleury Filho on 25 March signed contracts 
to refinance the Sao Paulo Government's debts to the Bank of 
Brazil, the Treasury's agent. Three billion dollars, involving 
debts contracted with the Federal Savings Bank, the National 
Bank for Economic and Social Development, and the Bank of Brazil 
and allocated for investments, have been refinanced. The debt's 
rollover will be indexed using the IGPM, Market Prices General 
Index, or the TR, Referential Interest Rate. The contracts call 
for 240 monthly installments. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO 
in Portuguese 26 Mar 94 Economy Section p B5) 
  Sao Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Parana States lose $560 
million per year from a commonplace maneuver in oil and oil 
by-products: fabricated interstate fuel sales to dodge ICMS, 
Goods and Services Movement Tax, collection. This type of fraud 
totals $1 billion throughout our country. Illegal trade 
operations involve 35 percent of total oil by-products sales in 
our country. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 27 
Mar 94 Economic Section p B11) 
  Braspetro, Petrobras International, Inc., is negotiating to 
prospect for and produce oil and natural gas in Peru and 
Bolivia. In 1993, Braspetro produced an average of 22,900 
barrels of oil per day in five countries: Angola, Argentina, 
England, the United States, and Ecuador. In Colombia, Braspetro 
will begin producing 600 barrels per day in the Llanos basin, 
while it will perform exploratory work in Libya and Norway. In 
1994, Braspetro will expand its production to 31,000 barrels per 
day, investing $160 million. In Argentina, Braspetro reduced its 
participation in the San Julian maritime basin from 53.5 to 33.5 
percent. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 29 Mar 94 
Special Section p 3) 
  Brazilian oil reserves stand at 3.8 billion barrels, 5.5 
percent higher than at the end of 1992. This reserve will last 
16 years based on average production of approximately 700,000 
barrels per day. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 29 
Mar 94 Special Section p 4) 
  Agriculture Minister Synval Guazzeli and Nidero Maki, vice 
president of Japan International Cooperation Agency, on 29 March 
signed a contract for financing the third phase of the 
Brazilian-Japanese Cooperation Program for the development of 
the Cerrado region -- the Prodecer III project. The project 
involves agricultural development of 40,000 hectares in Maranhao 
and Tocantins States. The Prodecer III project will get an 
investment of $138 million. Japan will provide $83 million and 
Brazil $55 million. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in 
Portuguese 30 Mar 94 p B4) 

</TEXT>

