<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Guerrilla Group Begins Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Guerrilla Group Begins Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3103202994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3103202994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "NTC News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A new guerrilla group has begun to operate in 
Colombia. It calls itself Total Democracy [Democracia Total] or 
Radical Democracy [Democracia Radical]. According to the DAS 
[Administrative Department of Security] Intelligence Department, 
the organization is made up of former members from the M-19 [19 
April Movement] and Faith, Peace, and Freedom [EPL] who are 
dissidents from the peace process. 
  The new organization's military targets are the presidential 
candidates, congress members, bankers, industrialists, and their 
former comrades, whom they accuse of treason. The director of 
the DAS Intelligence Department pointed out that documents found 
during an operation carried out by the DAS anti-kidnapping group 
disclosed that the guerrillas were planning multiple attacks to 
announce their subversive organization. 
  [Begin DAS Intelligence Director Ricardo Villarraga Franco 
recording] They think the subversive struggle should be 
transferred to the cities; that their support in the rural areas 
is not as large as they would like. They want to carry out 
selective attacks, as they themselves say, against the 
bourgeoisie in the country. [end recording] 
  Villarraga Franco insists this new guerrilla organization 
has 
recruited at least 20 percent of the former fighters of the four 
subversive organizations that demobilized. In addition, he said 
they are opposed to the tactics used by the National Guerrilla 
Coordinating Board. 
  The main topic of the most recent Security Council held at 
the Defense Ministry was the appearance of Total Democracy. The 
authorities feel this group cannot be underestimated, because it 
has grown in strength and military capability. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

