<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY3103222094 </F>
<F P=103> PY3103222094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Peru monitored through 31 
March. 
  The executive branch approved through Supreme Decree No. 
07-94-RE an agreement with the ROK Government on investments 
promotion and protection. This ratifies an agreement signed in 
June 1993 in Seoul. (Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 21 Mar 94 p B2) 
  Three new banks, the Solventa Bank, the Labor Bank, and the 
El Libertador Bank, are awaiting the Banking and Insurance 
Superintendency's authorization to begin operations in Peru. 
The new banks are supported by Chilean investors. (Lima EL 
PERUANO in Spanish 21 Mar 94 p A1) 
  One year after recommencing exploratory drilling activities 
in the jungle, Petroperu, State Petroleum Agency, again struck 
oil in lot No. 8 of the Pavayacu and Chambira projects, with a 
daily production rate of 6,000 barrels of oil. Lot No. 8 is 
located in the northwestern region of the Amazon basin. The 
Pavayacu discovery in lot No. 147D will allow the extraction of 
4,000 barrels of oil daily while the Chambira discovery in lot 
No. 123XCD will allow the extraction of 2,000 barrels of oil 
daily. Four companies operating on the continental shelf, the 
northern off-shore area, and the jungle, are producing about 
130,000 barrels of oil daily while the consumption rate totals 
150,000 barrels of oil daily. In the 1970's, daily oil 
production totaled 200,000 barrels. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in 
Spanish 22 Mar 94 p 5) 
  Manuel Vasquez Perales, the Financial Development 
Corporation 
board of directors chairman, announced on 18 March that two 
credit lines totaling $115 million have been approved for this 
year. A $90 million credit line was secured from the Andean 
Development Corporation for small- and medium-size enterprises. 
A $25 million credit line will be used to support the 
transformation of private companies and companies being 
privatized. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 19 Mar 94 p 3) 
  The World Bank on 19 March announced the approval of a $150 
million loan for Peru to finance a transportation reconditioning 
project for highways. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 19 Mar 94 p 
1) 
  Southern Peru Copper Corporation, SPCC, secured a $50 
million 
loan from Japan's Mitsui and Co. Ltd. for a $300 million SPCC 
investment program to increase copper production and improve 
SPCC operations with an emphasis on environmental protection. 
(Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 20 Mar 94 p A6) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

