Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomatic Mission To Open in Barbados </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomatic Mission To Open in Barbados </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL3103221794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1821 
GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL3103221794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Next week, Cuba will open a diplomatic mission in 
Barbados, which will help promote commercial, cultural, and 
sports relations with all eastern Caribbean as part of Cuba's 
integration into that region. 
  Cuba and Barbados established diplomatic relations on 8 
December 1992 [as heard], but now the opportunity to establish a 
mission in Bridgetown has arisen because of Cuba's closer ties 
with the Anglo-Caribbean community, Caricom. 
  Lazaro Cabezas, Cuba's current ambassador to eastern 
Caribbean, stressed that the main objectives of his mission are 
to strengthen economic and commercial ties as well as to promote 
culture and sports ties. Cabezas represents Cuba in St. Vincent 
and the Grenadines, the Bahamas, St. Lucia, and Trinidad and 
Tobago. The only countries in that region yet to formalize 
diplomatic ties with Cuba are Dominica, St. Kitts and Nevis, and 
Antigua and Barbuda. 

</TEXT>

