<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister on Possible State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister on Possible State of Emergency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA3103232094 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
0400 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA3103232094 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on a news conference by Government Minister Danilo </F>
Parinello with unidentified reporters in Guatemala City on 31 
March; from the "Telepress" newscast -- recorded] 
  [Text] At a news conference this afternoon, Government 
Minister Danilo Parinello addressed the issue of a possible 
state of emergency. 
  [Begin recording] [Parinello] We cannot rule out that 
possibility. We have given this issue broad discussion, and we 
cannot discard it. 
  [Unidentified reporter] The government communique states 
there are groups instigating all this commotion. Do you believe 
any specific group is responsible? 
  [Parinello] At this specific moment, no, but we are 
investigating. We have several investigation teams working all 
over the country trying to determine who might be responsible 
for this and initiating the appropriate legal action. 
  [Reporter] Is there any relation between this case and the 
incidents at Santa Lucia Cotzumalguapa due to the instigation 
factor? 
  [Parinello] This could be part of a collective psychosis 
that 
stems from this campaign, which is not spontaneous, including 
graffiti in cities, along highways, walls, and so on. Things 
such as this have happened all throughout history and all over 
the world whenever someone manages to agitate the people enough 
to create a type of collective psychosis. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

