<H3> <TI>   Government Suspends 1 May Workers Parade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Suspends 1 May Workers Parade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0104181694 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1637 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0104181694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Havana, 1 Apr (NOTIMEX) -- The Fidel Castro 
government decided to suspend the traditional 1 May workers 
parade and instead summoned the National Assembly of the 
People's Government [ANPP] to discuss issues related to the 
severe adjustment program to deal with the persistent economic 
crisis. The unusual decision to suspend the parade was 
announced Thursday by Pedro Ross Leal, secretary general of the 
Central Organization of the Cuban Workers Federation (CTC), who 
instead called for additional work shifts in order to ensure the 
success of the sugar harvest, the country's main industry. The 
summons to an extraordinary ANPP session was suggested this week 
by Castro in a speech during the closing ceremony of a plenary 
meeting of the CTC National Committee. 
  The colorful 1 May parade, to which Cuba would usually 
invite 
other countries' leftist political party leaders, was used by 
the government as a virtual plebiscite of workers support for 
the Cuban revolution. During a meeting with CTC leaders, Castro 
pointed out on that date [1 May], "there would be no better 
homage to workers" than the discussion by the ANPP deputies of 
the proposals by the "workers parliament" to clean-up the 
country's finances. 
  Included among the measures to be discussed during the 
assembly are those dealing with a tax system, a moratorium on 
subsidies to the consumption of goods and services, the closing 
down of inefficient companies, price increases, as well as 
cutting the state payroll. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

