<H3> <TI>   Praises Athletes' Role in Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Praises Athletes' Role in Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0104212894 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1800 
GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0104212894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 1 April, the World-Class Sports Conference 
featured an address by Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina on the 
principal points of Cuba's foreign policy and the role that 
sports plays in it: 
  [Begin Robaina recording] I must stress that our most 
significant ambassadors are in the field of sports. Athletes 
like Sotomayor, Ana Fidelia, and many others can attract 100,000 
people to a stadium. These athletes can tackle the most diverse 
issues. None of our diplomats, not the most acclaimed or 
trained, can in such a short period achieve what one of our 
modest athletes can -- transmit Cuba's image abroad. 
  I just spoke with our trainer in Thailand. During the first 
official meeting in Bangkok with that country's foreign 
minister, the number one issue of the talks was Cuba's trainer 
there. They wanted to know if we had more and how we do it. I 
believe this reflects not only what has already been 
accomplished, but what we are willing to do and are capable of 
doing. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

